font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">also </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">means that teachers have access t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">o a greater breadth of continuing professional development and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are able </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to work </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">with their counterparts in other schools</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> on areas of common interest. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Our experience as an Academy sponsor is that having a good relationship with the local authority support</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s the transition to Academy status.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Giving local authorities a role in the choice of academy sponsor </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">should increase the proportion of sponsored Academies that are established in a similarly collaborative manner, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">which is in the interests of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">whole </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">sch</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ool community.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Becoming an academy as part of a group is seen as a more cost-effective option for some primary school head teachers and governors than becoming a stand-alone academy, but </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">additional resource is needed to meet the costs of transition. </span></li></ul></td></tr></table><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">I </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">writ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> as Chief Executive of RSA Academies, an </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Academy </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">hain working with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a family of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">four </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Academies in the West Midlands.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">RSA Academies aims t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">o give learners the broad range of skills, qualifications, and experiences they need to thrive in their continuin</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">g education and the world of work</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, with a current focus on four priority areas:</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.05pt; padding-left:4.95pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Improving teaching and learning through purposeful partnerships;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.56pt; padding-left:4.44pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Enabling learners to achieve a broad range of qualifications, skills and competences;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.43pt; padding-left:5.57pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Supporting innovation in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> teaching and learning and a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> spirit of open-minded enquiry;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.56pt; padding-left:4.44pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Connecting teachers and learners to people, places and issues beyond the school gate.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">submission draws on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">both </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">my </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">direct experience of working with convertor and sponsored Academies, and on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">recent reports by the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">RSA</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and RSA’s partners on relevant issues.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Effectiveness of “academisation” in narrowing the gap for disadvantaged children</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> and the role of Academy Chains</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Education Committee ask</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> about the effectiveness of “academisation” in n</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">arrowing the gap for disadvantaged children</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and about the role of academy chains</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he term “academisation” cove</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rs two very different processes with the path to becoming a sponsored academy being very different to that for convertor academies.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The initial</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> tranche of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cademies were all sponsored </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cademies, in most cases replacing struggling schools.  In the early days </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cademy sponsorship involved the commitment of significant financial resource by the sponsor</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  W</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">hilst the requirement for the sponsor to make</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a financial contribution was quickly removed, sponsored </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cademies have continued to benefit from significant financial and other advantages.  The process of becoming a sponsored  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cademy has, until recently, been lengthy, with at least two to three terms </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">given to curriculum planning, the recruitment of appropriately qualified staff and so on.  The financial support also extended to a significant capital investment, in many cases resulting in brand new buildings.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ponsored </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cademies </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">re therefore generally</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> significantly different to their predecessor schools in terms of curriculum, senior staff, policies and approach as well as carrying a new name, new uniform and so on.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Since 2010 sponsored academies have been joined by a new wave of convertor academies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> These now </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">outnumber sponsored academies, comprising </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">70% of all </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cademies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  Only schools that are judged to be good or outstanding are able to apply to be convertor academies.  The conversion process is generally quick, taking </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">3-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">4 months, with none of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">work on curriculum changes, staff structure or building works associated with sponsored Academies.  As a result academy conversion </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">can</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">make little obvious </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">immediate </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">difference to pupils in the school: the senior leadership team and curriculum are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> unchanged, the buildings and school uniform remain the same, and the school retains its name.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Perhaps unsurprisingly there is little evidence that the legal change of status to become an Academy has any impact on standards or narrowing the gap.  The Acad</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">emies Commission concluded that, “academisation alone cannot be relied on for whole system improvement”</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and called for a forensic focus on both teaching and learning.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  The Commission also noted that academies were generally not making any great use of the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> new freedoms and flexibilities afforded by academy status.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There is, however, emerging evidence that belonging to a chain or group of schools can bring educational benefits.  Robert Hill’s report for the NCSL</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> on academy chains</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">found evidence that Academ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ies that were part of a chain</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of three or more schools had improved more rapidly than</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">stand-alone Academies, or those in a chain of two</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, both in terms of GCSE results and Ofsted </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rating, and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tentatively concluded </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that there was </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">evidence of a “positive chain</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> effect”.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">RSA Academies’ experience working with four Academies, which include both convertor and sponsored Academies, suggests that becoming an Academy as part of a Family of schools </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">can </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">be a powerful driver for school improvement.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Examples </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of ways in which the four schools </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">within the RSA Family of Academies </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">have worked together to support school improvement </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">include:</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.05pt; padding-left:4.95pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A tailored programme of support offered by our outstanding convertor Academies to new schools joining the RSA Family:  Whitley</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Academy has provided support to Arrow Vale RSA Academy on a range of issues including curriculum planning, staff structures, and business systems both before and after they joined the RSA Family.  Arrow Vale’s headline results have improved from 49% of pu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">pils achieving 5+ GCSEs at A*-C </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">at the predecessor school </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in 2011 to 63% </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">at Arrow Vale RSA Academy </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in 2013.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.56pt; padding-left:4.44pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Joint </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">action</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> addressing common areas of need</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  This term RSA Academies </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">has </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">commissioned an experience</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> HMI to work with the four schools on the fur</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ther development of cross-curricular literacy and English, with the key findings and next steps shared at a seminar for all four schools.  This means that the schools are able to learn from one another as well as the HMI, and will be able to continue to le</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">arn from one another as they implement the changes.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.43pt; padding-left:5.57pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Greater breadth of continuing professional development (CPD) opportunities: good schools prioritise high quality CPD, but the opportunities to grow and develop in a single school can be limited, and scho</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ols </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">which do this well may </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">find themselves losing highly qualified staff on promotion to other schools.  RSA Academies is able to co-ordinate programmes from </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">individual </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">INSET days to long-term secondments.  As well as bringing immediate benefits to the sta</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ff taking part, working in this way also helps develop career paths within </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">our</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> family of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">academies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  </span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.56pt; padding-left:4.44pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Improved opportunities to work cross-phase:  Ipsley CE RSA Academy is the middle school feeder for Arrow Vale RSA Academy.  The three tier system is now</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> unusual within the English education system, and creates a particular set of challenges in terms of progression from Key Stage 3 to 4 and beyond.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Working with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the two schools as part of a single multi-academy trust is of hugely helpful in terms of contin</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">uity and progression.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The roles of the Secretary of State and local authorities</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Education Committee asks </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">about the role of the Secretary of State in intervening and supporting failing academies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and the functions and responsibilities of local authorities in relation to academies and free schools</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  These questions are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">inextricably linked.  Any changes to the Secretary of State’s role would have implications for local government, and vice versa.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There is a strong case to be made that the same local checks and balances should apply in respect of all schools in an area, irrespective of the institution’s legal status as an Academy, Church School or Community School.   If this is accepted, then local</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> authorities as currently constituted cannot reasonably be expected to take on an oversight role in relation to all schools because Academies are independent of the local authority and have no formal input into the decisions that the local authority makes.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he establishment of a new ‘Local Education Board’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the membership of which would extend beyond elected Members of the local authority and include staff and governors from the different types of schools in the area, including Academies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, would help to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">est</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ablish a level playing field within a highly diverse school system.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Whatever the name and precise nature of the local authority type body, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">endorse the recommendation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of the Academies Commission that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">: </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">‘Local authorities should embrace a new role in e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ducation, not as providers of schools or school improvement services, but as champions for children.  This would mean articulating a local and aspirational vision for education.  As champions for children, the local authority would capture local knowledge </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and intelligence by undertaking some scrutiny of education provision to ensure that it is meeting the needs and interests of young people in the area.’</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Flowing from this, local authorities need to have the lead </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">role in securing a sufficient supply of high</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> quality school places</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  This means that they should </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">decid</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> whether or where new school places are needed (or, indeed, whether a school should close)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, and should also be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">empowered to make recommendations to the Secretary of State about the preferred partne</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">r for a new sponsored Academy or free school in the expectation that reasonable recommendations would be agreed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As an Academy sponsor the establishment of a good working relationship with the local authority in which our two newest sponsored Academies is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> located has been extremely beneficial in supporting the transition to Academy status.  Giving local authorities a role in deciding the academy sponsor should increase the proportion of sponsored Academies that are established in a similarly collaborative </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">manner, which is in the interests of the whole school community.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Primary Academies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As the Education Select Committee note, take up of Academy status by primary schools has been much lower than for secondary schools.  HMCIs’ latest annual report indicat</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">es that only 1522 of the 16799 primary schools in England (9%) are academies, compared with 1798 of the 3326 secondary schools in England (54%).  This difference is marked, even taking into account that primary schools have only been able to become Academi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">es since 2010.  The grant maintained schools movement in the 1990s, which also offered greater autonomy to schools, was also more attractive to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">secondary</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> schools than </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">prima</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ry schools.  At its peak in 1998 3% of primary schools and 19% of secondary schools </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">were grant maintained.  </span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">RSA Academies currently works with three secondary schools and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">one</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> middle school</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, but does not yet include any primary schools</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  Talking to head teachers and governors of primary schools about the possibility of becoming an Academ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">y as part of the RSA Family, either as a sponsored or convertor Academy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> there seem to be a number of barriers that are more significant for primary than secondary schools:  </span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.05pt; padding-left:4.95pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The additional responsibilities in relation to areas such as</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> finance, HR and com</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">missioning</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> are much more daunting for primary schools, wh</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ich</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> generally do not have a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">bursar or other senior finance and/or business manager </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">with the skills and expertise to take this on.  </span></li></ol></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="2" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.56pt; padding-left:4.44pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Many primary schools continue to rely on their local authorities </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for a wide range of support services which are often well-regarded by the local schools.  Alternative providers may offer poor value for money for small schools</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">;</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 66.43pt; padding-left:5.57pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">RSA Academies is not unusual in working mainly with secondary schools, and primary schools ca</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n feel that their needs will not be well met or over-looked amongst a larger group of secondary schools.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.56pt; padding-left:4.44pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Whilst </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">many </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">outstanding secondary </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">academies </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">have moved </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">into sponsoring other academies, the outstanding primary schools I have spoken to have been reluctant to take this on, expressing anxiety about the sustainability of a long term arrangement, for example when their existing head teacher </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">moves on</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ol></ol><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  Joinin</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">g an Academy chain </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">or converting as a group of primary Academies would </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">mitigate these risks</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, and potentially result in economies of scale once the new arrangements were well established</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In the short term, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">however, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a considerable investment of time and mo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ney </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">would be</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> needed to establish the new arrangements, as well as someone to support and co-ordinate the conversion, and this resource is not currently available.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">5</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">RSA and Pearson (2013) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Unleashing Greatness:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> Getting the best from an academised system</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">he Report of the Academies Commission</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Hill, R. Dunford, J., Parish, N., Rea, S., Sandals</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">, L. (2012) </span><span style="font-